mpse into the future of the corridor. New infrastructural plans—supported by President Joe Biden, famously Amtrak’s biggest fan—envision ever-faster trains zipping along technologically advanced rails. Yet those tracks will literally sit atop a history that links the life of Frederick Douglass, who fled to freedom by boarding a train in Baltimore, to the Frederick Douglass Tunnel, which is expected to be the newest link in the corridor by 2032. Trains have long made the places that make America, and they still do.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aTRANSPORTATION / General.2bisacsh  acorridor, northeast, railroad, infrastructure, public works, railroad, region, train, place.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079731240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226822846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226822846/original  a978-3-11-079731-2  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles